      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "1. In a blender or food processor, pulse the anchovies, garlic cloves and salt until it forms somewhat of a paste. Add the egg yolks, lemon zest, lemon juice, dijon mustard, black pepper, and olive oil; blend until completely incorporated. While the blender or food processor is running, slowly stream in the vegetable oil, blending until the dressing is pale and thick. Mix in the parmesan cheese. Taste for seasoning, adding salt or pepper accordingly. Transfer to a container or bowl and store in the fridge, covered until ready to use. Can be made 3 days in advance.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "2. Preheat a stovetop grill pan over medium-high heat. Cut the romaine lettuce in half, lengthwise, keeping the root end in tact to keep the lettuce together while it grills. Brush the lettuce with oil, to prevent it from sticking to the grill. Place the lettuce on the preheated grill, cut side down, and cook for about 2 to 5 minutes, or until grill marks form. Flip over and continue to grill for another 3 to 4 minutes. Transfer to a plate and allow to cool.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "3. Cut the baguette in half, lengthwise, and brush with oil. Place the bread on hot grill, cut side down, and cook for about 3 to 5 minutes, or until grill marks form. Flip over and continue to grill for another 2 to 3 minutes. Transfer to a cutting board. While the bread is still warm, rub the charred cut side, with the garlic clove, grating it into the bread nooks and crannies. Cut into a medium dice and arrange on a baking sheet. Place in a 350° oven for about 15 minutes or until crispy and golden brown. Remove from oven and allow to cool.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "4. Place the chicken cutlets into a medium bowl. Season with salt, pepper, paprika, garlic powder and 1 tablespoon oil. Stir until evenly incorporated. Place chicken onto hot grill, in one even layer. Grill for about 5 to 7 minutes. Flip over and continue to cook on second side for another 4 to 6 minutes. Transfer to a plate and allow to rest for about 5 minutes before slicing. Slice into thin pieces.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "5. Cut the lettuce into small strips and toss into a large mixing bowl. Add the croutons, sliced chicken, shaved parmesan and a bit of the dressing, or as much as you’d like. Toss to evenly combine and serve right away. Enjoy!",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Spin leaves dry first. Whisk dressing ingredients until thick and pourable. Dress at the table, not in the kitchen, so it stays evenly coated.",
              "cause": "Dressing not emulsified, or salad too wet.",
              "symptom": "Dressing pools at the bottom of the bowl"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Combine everything cold and dress just before serving. Sturdy leaves (kale, chicory, romaine) cope with sitting; spinach and rocket don't.",
              "cause": "Dressed too early, or fruit/cheese added warm.",
              "symptom": "Leaves wilted by the time it reached the table"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Three parts oil to one part acid is the classic ratio. Adjust with a squeeze of lemon if it's flat, or a splash more oil if it's sharp.",
              "cause": "Wrong oil-to-acid ratio in the dressing.",
              "symptom": "Salad tastes too oily"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Toss the leaves with dressing first, then scatter cheese, nuts, croutons on top. Don't toss again after garnishing.",
              "cause": "Heavy ingredients added before tossing.",
              "symptom": "Toppings ended up in the bottom"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Add-protein: top with grilled chicken, halloumi, or a soft-boiled egg for a main-course salad.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Crunch upgrade: scatter toasted nuts or seeds on top, pumpkin, almond, sunflower.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Best fresh. Leftovers keep two days in the fridge; reheat covered with a splash of liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
